english:
  title: Preface to the Departure of Han Attendant-Censor, Newly Appointed Inspector of Provinces
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my youth, I loved reading in the mountains, and I can still recall those old haunts with vivid clarity. Yet nothing stays with me more than the day I begged for rice at Gold Valley.

    Three of us—the current Attendant-Censor Han, the Ministry official Zhang, and myself—ventured into the sea-bound peaks of Qiaotong to study among its isolated heights. We were drawn to that desolate place where few mortals tread, hoping to make it our long home. But hunger in the mountains proved unbearable, and we turned back toward the capital. From our boat, gazing upon the western mountains, one of us spoke: "The Peony Peak south of Pyongju was also an ancient scholar's refuge. Why not go there?" So we commissioned Zhang to return and watch over our two households, pressed the boatmen westward, and made our way through reed beds for six or seven li. As twilight descended and our legs could carry us no further, I had no choice but to beg rice from the keeper of Gold Valley station. How foolish I was then in my desperation! Yet the spirit Mencius spoke of—that vast, inborn righteousness—dwelt within me, so evident that it could not be hidden. The innkeeper perceived this truth and treated me with unexpected kindness.

    The ancient gentlemen perfected their hearts through hardship and adversity, turning a single day of want into lifelong gain. All depends on how one conducts oneself. Why should I measure honor and shame by fine carriages and elegant dress or by rags and straw sandals?

    Han and I both passed the examination in the year of Xinsi together, and again achieved success together in Guisi. He is seven years my senior, superior to me in learning and letters alike. As for his integrity—even the rank of prime minister could not sway him, for he disdains the corruption of bending truth to please the world. Since gaining office, I have never ceased to feel shame at my own compromises. Yet he remained in minor posts, as if resigned to humble service for life. Now he enters the Censorate with distinction, advancing to the rank of Attendant-Censor—truly, he has met his moment. How different from those days at the station! Whether we two have remained unchanged in our principles, I cannot say.

    For an official at court, position and salary matter little; what matters is the freedom to practice one's principles. The Attendant-Censor impeaches wrongdoing, challenges the ruler's errors from above, questions the minister's righteousness from below—the whole court trembles at his presence. The Inspector of Provinces holds grave responsibility: representing the throne in sacred rites, observing the customs of the land, dispensing rewards and punishments with supreme authority. Local governors serve with utmost deference; they scrutinize even the smallest preference in food and drink, daring not to offend. To claim that one cannot fulfill one's ambitions in such positions—I do not believe it. An official bearing both titles must surely kindle his own resolve.

    The gentlemen of court compose verses praising his departure. The Attendant-Censor said: "The preface must come from Mogeun—only then will it satisfy me." I confess I do not love writing, nor do I write well; Han knows this truth. Yet he insisted on my hand because he knows I will not flatter him. So I recount our old wanderings, hoping this preface reminds him never to abandon what he has learned.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mencius's concept of haoran zhiqi (浩然之氣)—the vast, inborn moral righteousness—refers to an internal spiritual strength that cannot be concealed, even in poverty.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "high carriages and four horses" versus "straw sandals" represents the contrast between wealth and poverty, neither of which should determine one's moral worth.
  - key: ''
    value: Mogeun (牧隱) was Lee Saek's own pen name or scholarly sobriquet, so the addressee is requesting Lee's personal endorsement of his virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Gold Valley (金谷) refers to an ancient site associated with literary gatherings, making the begging there especially poignant—a reversal of its noble associations.
